e dynamic coverage class isn't tracking API calls as expected. It seems like the writeObject method is invoking the right bytecode, but maybe it didn't run fully after the second attempt? I'm considering how tampered class descriptors and non-recorded private methods might impact JDK serialization. Maybe the dynamic access tool isn't capturing coverage due to its exclusion of arrays. I think the replacement process needs a closer look after the writeObject call to clarify this issue.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring serialization challenges**\\n\\nI’m trying to understand the flow of return types in readObject and how the API transitions byte arrays after resolution. It seems that the library's in.readObject() gives me a byte array, which may not be captured correctly. The tracked call site might only cover non-array object serialization. If the user needs coverage, I should consider cases where ProvXDHPrivateKey.readObject reads a non-byte array. However, I can't change the argument for writeObject, and getEncoded() seems to always return byte[], complicating things further.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering object replacement in serialization**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using ObjectOutputStream.replaceObject for instrumentation, but I'm wondering if the coverage sees the object before it gets replaced, which might not be enough. It seems that the dynamic-access coverage only kicks in when serialization involves reflection for classes that need configuration, but byte arrays don’t require that. I’m curious whether the replacement occurs before or during the nested write, as that could significantly affect what gets captured.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating native image support**\\n\\nI'm pondering about native image support and wondering if the class bytes defined at runtime are unsupported. It seems like I might need to catch some sort of NativeImageSupport error. Yet, for JVM dynamic coverage, I should consider how call sites in a loaded class are affected. There’s quite a bit to unpack here regarding compatibility and functionality, and I'm trying to figure out the best way to approach this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Error Handling**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how to handle errors, especially if something isn’t supported. An AssertionError might pop up regarding NativeImageSupport, but I'm wondering if I really need a custom loader for that. It might be simpler to use `ObjectInputStream.resolveClass` to map the active descriptor to `Class.forName(PROVIDER_PRIVATE_KEY_CLASS_NAME)` with the system class. Current solutions are using string rewriting and default resolution, but I'm still exploring all angles here.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering security provider integration**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether to add `@BeforeAll` with `Security.addProvider`. The BouncyCastleFipsProvider currently returns a new provider but hasn't been added yet. I've confirmed that KeyPairGenerator works with the provider object, but serialization doesn't seem to be functioning. It makes me wonder if the dynamic agent is relying on JUnit tests in native-image runtime rather than JVM, which might cause deserialization issues due to unregistered serial classes. Hmmm, this is quite complex!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java encryption test**\\n\\nI think I need to add a direct test for the active class using `KeyFactory.getInstance(\\\"X25519\\\", provider).generatePrivate(new PKCS8EncodedKeySpec(...))`. On Java 21, it returns Prov11 due to MR, but it’s interesting to consider how the \\\"XDH\\\" algorithm might relate to a base mapping. I should look up the ProvEdEC base mapping and read those parts. There's a lot to consider here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ummzfB4xItK2L8XFbU7m2uuS|fc_06fcb496b6589a68016a3fbd0878ac81959cd53f5539ade32d", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/fo